WEBVTT

00:01.400 --> 00:03.433
♪ ♪

00:03.433 --> 00:04.666
TOM:
Sidney, my younger brother.

00:04.666 --> 00:06.766
♪ ♪

00:06.766 --> 00:09.166
SIDNEY:
I've underestimated you,
Miss Heywood.

00:09.166 --> 00:11.066
OTIS:
I never cared about your
fortune.

00:11.066 --> 00:12.666
What difference does it make
now?

00:12.666 --> 00:13.766
Charlotte...

00:13.766 --> 00:14.800
Yes?

00:15.766 --> 00:17.133
MAN:
Fire!

00:17.133 --> 00:19.466
TOM:
My situation is very grave
indeed, Sidney.

00:19.466 --> 00:21.466
SIDNEY:
I have been obliged
to engage myself

00:21.466 --> 00:22.533
to Mrs. Eliza Campion.

00:22.533 --> 00:24.266
I wish you every happiness--
excuse me.

00:24.266 --> 00:29.966
♪ ♪

00:30.833 --> 00:37.533
♪ ♪

00:41.166 --> 00:45.466
♪ ♪

00:51.266 --> 00:54.833
♪ ♪

01:06.000 --> 01:11.166
♪ ♪

01:21.800 --> 01:27.366
(lively music playing,
people clapping along)

01:27.366 --> 01:34.266
(people cheering and whooping)

01:34.266 --> 01:36.100
(music fades)

01:38.166 --> 01:42.733
♪ ♪

02:01.900 --> 02:08.033
(lively music playing,
people clapping along)

02:09.333 --> 02:13.866
(music fades)

02:13.866 --> 02:19.333
♪ ♪

02:33.433 --> 02:37.566
♪ ♪

02:49.100 --> 02:53.100
♪ ♪

03:03.866 --> 03:09.700
(sobbing)

03:09.700 --> 03:15.733
♪ ♪

03:24.633 --> 03:27.933
♪ ♪

03:39.666 --> 03:43.500
(birds chirping)

03:43.500 --> 03:46.633
This had better be worth it,
child,

03:46.633 --> 03:49.500
or I shall have you strangled!

03:49.500 --> 03:51.966
(carriage approaching)

03:54.466 --> 03:56.466
You see? I told you.

03:58.366 --> 04:01.433
♪ ♪

04:09.633 --> 04:14.233
♪ ♪

04:35.733 --> 04:38.966
Thank you, Lord Kingsley.

04:41.366 --> 04:42.766
Oh!

04:42.766 --> 04:44.666
As for your proposal,

04:44.666 --> 04:46.733
I would sooner be boiled alive.

04:49.733 --> 04:51.933
Although,
I do admire your carriage.

04:51.933 --> 04:54.300
♪ ♪

04:54.300 --> 04:56.300
(doorbell ringing)

04:58.333 --> 04:59.800
TOM:
Lord Kingsley was greatly
offended.

04:59.800 --> 05:01.333
I was candid.

05:01.333 --> 05:03.533
And that is a virtue.

05:03.533 --> 05:04.533
Is it not, Miss Hankins?

05:04.533 --> 05:06.200
Quite so.

05:06.200 --> 05:07.200
Brother?

05:07.200 --> 05:09.333
Um, yes, uh, but...

05:09.333 --> 05:12.066
But there is much to be said
for tact.

05:12.066 --> 05:15.866
I showed him as much respect
as any fortune hunter deserves.

05:17.733 --> 05:19.466
I'm not a natural guardian,
Mary.

05:19.466 --> 05:21.800
She is quite indifferent to my
counsel.

05:21.800 --> 05:24.133
Give her time, dearest.

05:24.133 --> 05:26.700
It has only been three months
since Sidney's death.

05:26.700 --> 05:29.766
It has affected her far more
than she would admit.

05:29.766 --> 05:31.366
Hm.

05:31.366 --> 05:33.366
I believe what she needs,

05:33.366 --> 05:37.033
more than anything,
is another friend.

05:37.033 --> 05:40.666
Happily, one is on the way.

05:40.666 --> 05:42.333
♪ ♪

05:42.333 --> 05:45.266
ALISON:
It was so kind of the Parkers
to lend us their carriage.

05:45.266 --> 05:47.933
When I am married,
I shall have one just like this.

05:47.933 --> 05:50.033
And four footmen!

05:50.033 --> 05:53.133
Only the four?

05:53.133 --> 05:55.200
I cannot decide who I am most
excited to meet.

05:55.200 --> 05:58.166
They were all so vivid
in your letters!

05:58.166 --> 05:59.933
I know Miss Lambe
and I are destined

05:59.933 --> 06:02.166
to be the greatest
of friends.

06:03.800 --> 06:05.433
Look, Charlotte!

06:05.433 --> 06:08.733
The sea!

06:08.733 --> 06:11.400
Are you not excited to be
returning?

06:11.400 --> 06:15.766
♪ ♪

06:25.400 --> 06:29.300
♪ ♪

06:36.866 --> 06:40.366
(children laughing)

06:40.366 --> 06:44.933
♪ ♪

06:44.933 --> 06:47.366
TOM:
Welcome!

06:47.366 --> 06:49.433
(laughing)

06:49.433 --> 06:50.933
Oh, hello!

06:50.933 --> 06:52.100
How you've grown!

06:52.100 --> 06:54.233
I shall be as tall
as Mama soon!

06:56.566 --> 06:59.300
Tom, you are so generous
to invite us both!

06:59.300 --> 07:01.133
This is my sister, Alison.
Pleasure.

07:01.133 --> 07:02.666
Come on.

07:03.866 --> 07:10.800
♪ ♪

07:10.800 --> 07:13.833
SIDNEY (voiceover):
I had hoped when I returned home

07:13.833 --> 07:16.433
to be able to make you a
proposal of marriage,

07:16.433 --> 07:18.800
but that cannot be.

07:18.800 --> 07:20.600
The fact is, I have been obliged

07:20.600 --> 07:23.800
to engage myself
to Mrs. Eliza Campion.

07:25.433 --> 07:27.566
Please believe me that if there
was any other way

07:27.566 --> 07:30.033
to resolve Tom's situation,
I would.

07:30.033 --> 07:31.200
JENNY:
We'll take you to your bedroom.

07:38.233 --> 07:43.566
♪ ♪

07:43.566 --> 07:46.533
I do hope Mary passed on my
sympathies.

07:46.533 --> 07:50.033
Yes, yes, thank you.

07:58.866 --> 08:03.600
♪ ♪

08:14.200 --> 08:17.500
I was surprised to learn Sidney
was in Antigua.

08:17.500 --> 08:18.800
Uh, we were as surprised
as you.

08:18.800 --> 08:19.800
We cannot account for it.

08:19.800 --> 08:21.733
We instructed an agent in
Antigua

08:21.733 --> 08:24.033
with repatriating his
possessions.

08:24.033 --> 08:26.966
We hope he might be able to find
some kind of explanation.

08:26.966 --> 08:29.466
TOM:
If only

08:29.466 --> 08:31.233
he'd never gone,

08:31.233 --> 08:33.600
he'd have been spared the yellow
fever and still be with us.

08:33.600 --> 08:35.933
It, it is some comfort
to know

08:35.933 --> 08:38.933
that he found such happiness
with Eliza before he,

08:38.933 --> 08:40.600
before we lost him.
(footsteps approaching)

08:40.600 --> 08:42.833
What a beautiful house!

08:42.833 --> 08:44.600
I cannot wait to see the town!

08:44.600 --> 08:46.433
MARY:
Once you're both settled,

08:46.433 --> 08:47.466
you shall meet Georgiana for
some tea

08:47.466 --> 08:48.600
in the new Assembly Room.

08:48.600 --> 08:49.933
TOM:
But first I must

08:49.933 --> 08:51.333
show you the promenade!

08:51.333 --> 08:52.533
Oh, I should love to see it.

08:52.533 --> 08:54.100
MARY:
Georgiana will be so pleased
to see you.

08:54.100 --> 08:56.766
Mr. Hankins and his sister have
kindly offered

08:56.766 --> 08:58.066
to become her chaperones.

08:58.066 --> 09:02.666
But the arrangement could not
be called ideal.

09:02.666 --> 09:09.266
HANKINS AND BEATRICE (loudly):
♪ Bread of Heaven,
bread of Heaven ♪

09:09.266 --> 09:13.000
♪ Feed me till I want no more ♪

09:13.000 --> 09:15.966
♪ Want no more ♪

09:15.966 --> 09:17.000
(clears throat softly)

09:17.000 --> 09:19.600
♪ Feed me till ♪

09:19.600 --> 09:26.466
♪ I want no more ♪

09:26.466 --> 09:29.566
You must sing up,
my dear!

09:29.566 --> 09:30.833
How is the Lord to hear you

09:30.833 --> 09:33.400
unless you raise your sweet
voice to His ear?

09:33.400 --> 09:37.833
I have long since concluded
that the Lord is deaf.

09:37.833 --> 09:40.366
The Lord is not deaf,
Miss Lambe.

09:40.366 --> 09:45.100
Then why does He persist
in ignoring my prayers?

09:45.100 --> 09:46.166
♪ ♪

09:46.166 --> 09:47.566
Brother...

09:47.566 --> 09:51.000
(stammers):
Uh, Miss Lambe,
the Lord does not ignore...

09:51.000 --> 09:53.300
GEORGIANA:
I'm going to be late
for Miss Charlotte!

09:53.300 --> 09:55.466
Miss Lambe?

09:57.566 --> 10:02.800
(seagulls squawking)

10:02.800 --> 10:09.000
♪ ♪

10:18.933 --> 10:21.733
TOM:
As you can see, my dears,
Sanditon is fast becoming

10:21.733 --> 10:24.600
the most desirable destination
on the south coast.

10:24.600 --> 10:25.833
ARTHUR:
And now I'm Tom's right hand,

10:25.833 --> 10:27.833
I've been planning some schemes
of my own.

10:27.833 --> 10:30.100
A pagoda, and even a theater!

10:30.100 --> 10:31.366
How exciting!

10:31.366 --> 10:33.166
I gather Mr. Stringer
is doing well in London.

10:33.166 --> 10:35.333
Yes, by all accounts,
he is well on his way

10:35.333 --> 10:37.300
to becoming
a master architect.

10:37.300 --> 10:38.700
Ah, Lord Cramond,
good morning!

10:38.700 --> 10:40.700
Morning.
I trust we shall see you
at the parade?

10:40.700 --> 10:42.300
A parade?

10:42.300 --> 10:43.600
Your timing could hardly be
better.

10:43.600 --> 10:46.200
We await the arrival of Colonel
Lennox and his company.

10:46.200 --> 10:48.366
They are to remain
the whole summer.

10:48.366 --> 10:50.466
A colonel and his company?
How thrilling!

10:50.466 --> 10:52.633
Yes, decorated for his bravery
at Waterloo.

10:52.633 --> 10:55.066
And, as if you required any
further proof

10:55.066 --> 10:56.366
that Sanditon has arrived,

10:56.366 --> 10:58.533
we have even attracted our
own artist.

10:58.533 --> 11:00.000
ARTHUR:
Charles Lockhart.

11:00.000 --> 11:01.466
I daresay you've heard of him--
he's a portraitist!

11:01.466 --> 11:03.766
Good morning,
Mr. Lockhart.
CHARLES: It is,

11:03.766 --> 11:05.033
Mr. Parker.

11:05.033 --> 11:06.766
I've just braved the waves
and I feel quite reborn!

11:06.766 --> 11:08.800
Nothing like the sting...

11:08.800 --> 11:10.033
(slaps chest):
...of salt on skin

11:10.033 --> 11:12.600
to rouse the senses.

11:12.600 --> 11:16.833
Ladies.

11:16.833 --> 11:18.833
(Tom clears throat)

11:18.833 --> 11:20.600
(talking quietly)

11:20.600 --> 11:23.133
I fear we look hopelessly
parochial.

11:23.133 --> 11:25.066
We must ask Papa to send us
money for clothes at once.

11:25.066 --> 11:26.766
We have little enough
to spare.

11:26.766 --> 11:28.233
It would be an investment.

11:28.233 --> 11:29.733
How are we to attract rich
husbands

11:29.733 --> 11:30.800
unless we look the part?

11:30.800 --> 11:32.166
I came here
to avoid all that!

11:32.166 --> 11:34.466
You came here to avoid
a certain man.

11:34.466 --> 11:36.066
Not marriage altogether.

11:36.066 --> 11:38.900
Why would you wish
to do that?

11:38.900 --> 11:43.566
♪ ♪

11:56.866 --> 11:58.800
What say you, Colonel?

11:58.800 --> 12:02.966
We've certainly faced harsher
battlefields.

12:05.500 --> 12:09.266
LADY DENHAM:
Around a hundred men, I'm told.

12:09.266 --> 12:12.533
And they march on Sanditon
tomorrow afternoon.

12:12.533 --> 12:15.066
ESTHER:
Don't you think it rather
peculiar?

12:15.066 --> 12:17.333
To the best of my knowledge,
we're not at risk of invasion.

12:17.333 --> 12:19.066
LADY DENHAM:
No, we're not from without,
perhaps,

12:19.066 --> 12:22.033
but sedition is sweeping the
country.

12:22.033 --> 12:25.433
And as landed gentry, it would
be our necks at the guillotine.

12:25.433 --> 12:29.733
I welcome a military presence.

12:29.733 --> 12:31.566
A hundred drunk,
unshaven libertines.

12:31.566 --> 12:33.233
Quite a civilizing influence.

12:33.233 --> 12:35.133
Not every soldier is a rascal.

12:35.133 --> 12:37.933
I've always had a certain
fondness for a red coat.

12:37.933 --> 12:40.766
My favorite brother was
a cavalryman.

12:40.766 --> 12:42.200
Maximilian.

12:42.200 --> 12:46.233
As long as they do not outstay
their welcome.

12:47.166 --> 12:49.533
I've been here
less than a week, Aunt.

12:49.533 --> 12:50.866
Yes, and I'm still not clear

12:50.866 --> 12:52.700
as to what purpose your stay
in the first place.

12:52.700 --> 12:57.500
A new husband should retain his
luster for a year, at least.

12:57.500 --> 12:59.066
Occasionally two.

12:59.066 --> 13:00.900
You've not tired of him
already?

13:00.900 --> 13:02.566
Quite the opposite.

13:02.566 --> 13:04.233
While he's away,
it's the perfect opportunity

13:04.233 --> 13:06.466
to visit
my favorite aunt.

13:06.466 --> 13:09.233
Hmm, how thoughtful
of you.

13:09.233 --> 13:13.833
♪ ♪

13:17.466 --> 13:20.433
Thank you.
Thank you-- thank you.

13:20.433 --> 13:22.266
Georgiana!

13:22.266 --> 13:24.333
I've been counting
the hours!

13:26.000 --> 13:28.600
My sister, Alison.

13:30.700 --> 13:34.500
GEORGIANA:
She and her brother are
well-meaning.

13:34.500 --> 13:35.966
Painfully so.

13:35.966 --> 13:38.933
And Tom Parker is a woefully
ineffective guardian,

13:38.933 --> 13:41.200
though he is determined
to see me married

13:41.200 --> 13:43.033
before my 21st birthday.

13:43.033 --> 13:45.500
I think he is just keen
to be rid of me,

13:45.500 --> 13:47.066
like his brother before him.

13:47.066 --> 13:49.400
Sidney was fonder of you than
you allow.

13:49.400 --> 13:51.100
Perhaps.

13:51.100 --> 13:52.500
Though now we shall never know.

13:52.500 --> 13:54.766
ALISON:
Is there any sugar?

13:54.766 --> 13:56.100
We are leading a boycott,

13:56.100 --> 13:58.233
in the hopes those plantation
owners

13:58.233 --> 13:59.766
who persist in keeping slaves

13:59.766 --> 14:02.833
will be forced to follow my
father's example.

14:02.833 --> 14:05.000
Forgive me, I thought we'd
abolished slavery.

14:05.000 --> 14:07.366
The law only prohibits the
buying and selling of slaves.

14:07.366 --> 14:10.000
As yet, there is no law
against owning them.

14:10.000 --> 14:11.833
Then I shall never have sugar
again.

14:13.433 --> 14:15.133
MAN:
Good day to you,
Miss Lambe.

14:15.133 --> 14:16.900
An admirer?

14:16.900 --> 14:19.866
I am besieged by fortune
hunters.

14:19.866 --> 14:22.133
Each day brings a fresh
proposal.

14:22.133 --> 14:23.466
That man in the corner proposed

14:23.466 --> 14:24.533
just this morning.

14:24.533 --> 14:26.500
(talking softly)

14:26.500 --> 14:28.233
You've not been tempted
to accept any of them?

14:28.233 --> 14:29.433
Why?

14:29.433 --> 14:31.766
I have never possessed such
power.

14:31.766 --> 14:32.900
The moment I marry,

14:32.900 --> 14:34.533
that will vanish.

14:34.533 --> 14:37.800
ALISON:
You are not the only one who's
been trying to evade a proposal.

14:39.100 --> 14:40.233
Charlotte?

14:40.233 --> 14:42.200
You made no mention in your
letters.

14:42.200 --> 14:43.900
CHARLOTTE:
Ralph Starling.

14:43.900 --> 14:46.266
He keeps a farm
in Willingden.

14:46.266 --> 14:48.166
Our father is... keen.

14:48.166 --> 14:49.366
More than keen.

14:49.366 --> 14:51.633
A proposal is a foregone
conclusion.

14:51.633 --> 14:54.800
But I have no desire to see
Charlotte marry sensible Ralph.

14:54.800 --> 14:56.533
GEORGIANA:
Neither do I.

14:56.533 --> 14:57.733
So, I have a plan.

14:57.733 --> 15:00.166
For us both to find husbands
here in Sanditon.

15:00.166 --> 15:01.166
Perhaps you could help us,

15:01.166 --> 15:03.100
Miss Lambe.

15:03.100 --> 15:06.266
I would like nothing more than
to see your sister find love,

15:06.266 --> 15:08.266
Miss Heywood.

15:08.266 --> 15:10.466
(coins jingle)
Thank you, sir.

15:11.933 --> 15:18.166
♪ ♪

15:18.166 --> 15:19.466
Who do you suppose that man is?

15:19.466 --> 15:20.566
CHARLOTTE:
Charles Lockhart.

15:20.566 --> 15:22.566
He's an artist.

15:23.966 --> 15:26.266
Looks rather pleased with
himself.

15:26.266 --> 15:33.333
♪ ♪

15:38.000 --> 15:40.066
Business is booming.

15:40.066 --> 15:42.266
ARTHUR:
Almost all our properties
are let.

15:42.266 --> 15:44.633
That is no reason to rest on
our laurels.

15:44.633 --> 15:46.133
What is next?

15:46.133 --> 15:48.700
Your grand plan seems to have
ground to a halt.

15:48.700 --> 15:50.033
By no means.

15:50.033 --> 15:52.433
But I will not proceed until
all the investment is secured.

15:52.433 --> 15:55.100
I've learned my lesson from
flying too close to the sun.

15:55.100 --> 15:59.000
I should hope so,
given half the town burnt down!

15:59.000 --> 16:01.100
Hence the regrettable fact that
your brother's widow

16:01.100 --> 16:03.800
now owns a large share of
Sanditon.

16:03.800 --> 16:06.266
That was a loan, my lady,
one I fully intend to pay back.

16:06.266 --> 16:08.133
Good.

16:08.133 --> 16:13.200
I am supposed to be the primary
investor, not some interloper!

16:13.200 --> 16:16.066
Although I should like to know
how you intend to pay her back,

16:16.066 --> 16:18.166
given the size of the debt.

16:18.166 --> 16:21.900
We shall find a way,
milady.
Indeed.

16:21.900 --> 16:24.366
And I do believe the first part
of the solution

16:24.366 --> 16:26.633
is marching into town this
afternoon.

16:26.633 --> 16:28.133
Forgive me, Mr. Parker,

16:28.133 --> 16:29.933
but how will the Army help your
situation?

16:29.933 --> 16:33.300
What is an army, ladies,
but a ready-made population,

16:33.300 --> 16:36.066
all looking
to spend, spend, spend?

16:36.066 --> 16:39.433
(birds chirping,
men calling in distance)

16:39.433 --> 16:40.766
I can't say I've ever understood
the appeal

16:40.766 --> 16:42.533
that soldiers are meant
to hold for our sex.

16:42.533 --> 16:45.533
Because they are brave
and noble and heroic.

16:45.533 --> 16:46.566
And frequently
handsome.

16:46.566 --> 16:47.733
Doubtless,
some are.

16:47.733 --> 16:49.300
Yet I cannot help thinking
those qualities

16:49.300 --> 16:51.233
are conferred on anyone in a
red coat,

16:51.233 --> 16:54.266
regardless of what
true character lies beneath.

16:54.266 --> 16:55.566
LENNOX:
Fraser!

16:55.566 --> 16:58.333
It appears we've been ambushed.

16:58.333 --> 17:01.100
Have mercy, ladies,
we are unarmed and outnumbered.

17:01.100 --> 17:03.100
Forgive us, sir,
we were...
It is I who should apologize.

17:03.100 --> 17:06.300
A gentleman at his ablutions

17:06.300 --> 17:07.600
is not a sight for fair eyes.

17:08.766 --> 17:11.133
Colonel Francis Lennox
at your service.

17:11.133 --> 17:14.666
And my aide,
Captain Fraser.
Ladies.

17:14.666 --> 17:16.033
Charlotte Heywood.

17:16.033 --> 17:17.266
My sister,
Miss Alison Heywood.

17:17.266 --> 17:18.300
Miss Georgiana Lambe.

17:18.300 --> 17:19.600
How do you do?

17:19.600 --> 17:21.900
We need to strengthen our
fortifications, Colonel.

17:21.900 --> 17:25.000
We cannot leave ourselves
so open to intruders.

17:25.000 --> 17:26.666
Should we be concerned by your
arrival, sir?

17:26.666 --> 17:29.700
Does it suggest that
Sanditon requires defending?
LENNOX: By no means.

17:29.700 --> 17:32.033
But should you receive
intelligence

17:32.033 --> 17:34.033
of an imminent invasion,
Miss Heywood,

17:34.033 --> 17:35.733
I hope you will be good enough
to share it.

17:35.733 --> 17:37.733
I shall keep my ear to the
ground.

17:37.733 --> 17:38.866
ALISON:
Will your family be joining you,

17:38.866 --> 17:40.766
Colonel?

17:40.766 --> 17:42.166
I have no such attachments.

17:42.166 --> 17:44.066
FRASER:
Ladies, perhaps

17:44.066 --> 17:46.400
I might escort you out?
Good day.

17:46.400 --> 17:48.066
We are quite capable of finding
our own way out, thank you, sir.

17:48.066 --> 17:52.666
♪ ♪

17:52.666 --> 17:55.266
(laughing)

17:56.533 --> 17:58.033
Saints alive, Fraser.

17:58.033 --> 18:00.366
Who was that?

18:00.366 --> 18:03.633
I didn't get her name.

18:03.633 --> 18:06.166
What is to be done with you,
man?

18:06.166 --> 18:07.433
LADY DENHAM (voiceover):
I don't suppose

18:07.433 --> 18:09.933
you've had any word
from your reprobate brother?

18:09.933 --> 18:11.566
Stepbrother--
mercifully not.

18:11.566 --> 18:14.866
I neither know nor care about
his whereabouts.

18:16.800 --> 18:21.100
(baby cooing)

18:23.833 --> 18:25.800
I imagine Lord Babington must be
growing impatient

18:25.800 --> 18:27.300
for an heir by now.

18:27.300 --> 18:28.900
It's not been
so very long.

18:28.900 --> 18:31.800
Eight-and-a-half months
should be ample.

18:31.800 --> 18:34.433
I assume you know what
is required?

18:34.433 --> 18:36.833
The mechanics?
Yes, thank you, Aunt.

18:36.833 --> 18:40.400
Then what is your excuse?

18:40.400 --> 18:41.800
Oh.

18:41.800 --> 18:44.333
(sighs)

18:44.333 --> 18:48.033
Lord Babington
and I agreed that

18:48.033 --> 18:50.566
I should come here while he's
away.

18:50.566 --> 18:54.866
Perhaps the, the sea air
might...

18:54.866 --> 18:57.766
That it might help me recover

18:57.766 --> 19:01.066
and perhaps Dr. Fuchs...
(exhales)

19:01.066 --> 19:02.466
Oh.

19:02.466 --> 19:04.766
Well, it's no good feeling sorry
for yourself.

19:04.766 --> 19:06.666
That will achieve nothing.

19:06.666 --> 19:10.133
And the sea air alone will
not do the trick.

19:10.133 --> 19:12.500
And nor will Fuchs--
the man's a charlatan.

19:12.500 --> 19:13.466
He saved your life.

19:13.466 --> 19:16.133
Oh, poppycock!

19:16.133 --> 19:18.366
I survived despite him.

19:18.366 --> 19:21.600
The man's a complete menace.

19:21.600 --> 19:26.733
♪ ♪

19:32.966 --> 19:34.833
(exhales)

19:41.133 --> 19:46.066
♪ ♪

19:46.066 --> 19:50.166
So you've been married for nine
months now,

19:50.166 --> 19:53.233
Lady Babington?
Yes.

19:53.233 --> 19:55.066
And yet, regrettably,

19:55.066 --> 19:57.733
you have not succeeded in
becoming schwanger.

19:57.733 --> 20:00.966
Uh, that is to say,
with child.

20:00.966 --> 20:04.300
No, Dr. Fuchs.

20:04.300 --> 20:07.100
I succeeded perfectly well
at conceiving.

20:07.100 --> 20:10.566
I was unable to... carry her.

20:12.133 --> 20:15.033
FUCHS:
How long ago did you lose
the infant?

20:15.033 --> 20:19.000
About a month.
And how far along?

20:22.966 --> 20:25.500
Five-and-a-half months.

20:27.400 --> 20:29.500
The doctors told me I came
perilously close

20:29.500 --> 20:32.000
to losing my own life.

20:32.000 --> 20:37.566
They said it would be dangerous,
fatal, even, to try again.

20:39.533 --> 20:41.933
Which only made me more
determined to prove them wrong.

20:41.933 --> 20:44.233
Well, what do you
suggest?

20:44.233 --> 20:48.266
I think the milk from my asses
will replenish her strength,

20:48.266 --> 20:52.233
but no doubt you have
some miraculous elixir to sell.

20:52.233 --> 20:55.633
Certainly, there are remedies
I can prepare

20:55.633 --> 20:58.000
for a woman in your position,
Lady Babington.

20:58.000 --> 21:01.466
But I must be honest,

21:01.466 --> 21:05.400
I cannot say
how efficacious they may be.

21:05.400 --> 21:08.500
It grieves me to say it,

21:08.500 --> 21:10.233
but perhaps God
does not intend

21:10.233 --> 21:13.300
for you to be a mother.
(gasps)

21:13.300 --> 21:15.266
I told you he would be no use.

21:16.566 --> 21:20.866
I will swallow any pill,
subject myself to any treatment.

21:22.366 --> 21:24.066
Please.

21:24.066 --> 21:28.233
I want to give my husband a
child.

21:28.233 --> 21:33.000
(dog barking)

21:34.466 --> 21:36.000
This May Day dress is far
too plain.

21:36.000 --> 21:38.166
Perhaps I could borrow one of
yours?

21:38.166 --> 21:40.366
Mary's shoes
are a perfect fit.

21:40.366 --> 21:43.300
Although I did have to stuff
a little paper in the toes.

21:43.300 --> 21:44.833
It's a parade, Alison,
not a ball.

21:44.833 --> 21:46.066
We are not the ones

21:46.066 --> 21:48.366
who are to be on display.
Are we not?

21:48.366 --> 21:50.100
A hundred soldiers, Charlotte.

21:50.100 --> 21:51.566
And I have read that one cannot
overstate

21:51.566 --> 21:53.700
the importance of a first
impression.

21:53.700 --> 21:56.500
But then you've already made
quite an impression.

21:56.500 --> 21:58.900
I speak of Colonel Lennox.

21:58.900 --> 22:00.500
We barely exchanged five words.

22:00.500 --> 22:02.533
Sometimes that is all it takes.
Alison,

22:02.533 --> 22:04.866
can a man and a woman not
exchange a passing glance

22:04.866 --> 22:06.933
without you supposing them
to be in love?

22:06.933 --> 22:09.100
I just want to see you happy
again, Charlotte.

22:09.100 --> 22:10.900
Is that so wrong?

22:10.900 --> 22:13.733
♪ ♪

22:13.733 --> 22:16.566
I fear all those books have
warped your view of the world.

22:19.033 --> 22:21.600
Love is not as simple as you
seem to think.

22:21.600 --> 22:23.966
Why should it not be?

22:26.633 --> 22:29.133
(seagulls squawking)

22:29.133 --> 22:30.400
MARY:
I fear my shoes are hurting you.

22:30.400 --> 22:33.300
By no means, they are far
too pretty to be painful.

22:33.300 --> 22:34.566
Well, it's a curious
thing,

22:34.566 --> 22:36.733
but since I returned
without Diana,

22:36.733 --> 22:39.533
all my former ailments
have vanished.

22:39.533 --> 22:42.400
(chuckles):
Having an occupation agrees
with me.

22:42.400 --> 22:45.933
A sense of purpose is altogether
galvanizing.

22:45.933 --> 22:48.966
You give me hope that I may soon
discover my life's purpose.

22:48.966 --> 22:54.100
I am no substitute for Sidney,
but I make myself useful to Tom.

22:54.100 --> 22:56.900
Although I worry for him.

22:56.900 --> 23:00.233
He can hardly bring himself
to speak Sidney's name.

23:00.233 --> 23:02.566
It is unwise to keep grief
bottled up.

23:03.666 --> 23:05.500
True.

23:05.500 --> 23:08.100
Since we don't have a grave
to mark him,

23:08.100 --> 23:11.533
I often light a candle in the
church and weep like a baby.

23:13.533 --> 23:15.766
I always feel much the better
for it.

23:15.766 --> 23:17.566
(clears throat softly)

23:17.566 --> 23:18.566
Enjoy the parade.

23:18.566 --> 23:20.100
Oh, you're not coming?

23:20.100 --> 23:23.900
Uh, I am not as excited about
the Army's arrival as some.

23:23.900 --> 23:26.100
I shall be taking tea
with Miss Lambe instead.

23:29.166 --> 23:32.733
♪ ♪

23:37.066 --> 23:39.600
Abstain from sugar
made by slaves.

23:39.600 --> 23:41.966
Abstain from sugar
made by slaves.

23:41.966 --> 23:44.666
LADY DENHAM:
What is this nonsense,
Miss Hankins?

23:44.666 --> 23:45.900
BEATRICE:
It is a movement of women

23:45.900 --> 23:48.266
who hope to bring about

23:48.266 --> 23:50.400
the total abolition of slavery,
Lady Denham.

23:50.400 --> 23:53.166
Radical nonsense!

23:53.166 --> 23:55.733
What good will denying
ourselves sugar do?

23:55.733 --> 23:58.766
Do you really think slavery
will be stopped

23:58.766 --> 24:01.866
by a few do-gooding ladies
at the seaside?

24:01.866 --> 24:04.666
It was Miss Lambe
who started the boycott

24:04.666 --> 24:06.333
in Sanditon, milady.
Oh.

24:06.333 --> 24:08.866
Quelle surprise!

24:08.866 --> 24:12.466
♪ ♪

24:12.466 --> 24:13.800
(crowd cheering)

24:13.800 --> 24:15.633
There's the colonel.

24:15.633 --> 24:18.333
(crowd cheering)

24:18.333 --> 24:20.333
Come on!

24:20.333 --> 24:23.166
♪ ♪

24:23.166 --> 24:26.966
(children screaming excitedly)

24:26.966 --> 24:32.066
(crowd cheering)

24:32.066 --> 24:36.800
♪ ♪

24:40.000 --> 24:45.733
♪ ♪

24:46.566 --> 24:48.666
Lady Denham,
Lady Babington.

24:48.666 --> 24:49.633
You remember Miss Heywood.

24:49.633 --> 24:52.500
And may I introduce
her sister,

24:52.500 --> 24:54.433
Miss Alison Heywood.

24:54.433 --> 24:57.533
Lady Denham, Lady Babington.
Oh.

24:57.533 --> 24:59.900
I rather thought
we'd seen the last of you.

24:59.900 --> 25:02.066
Sit down.

25:05.566 --> 25:06.833
ALISON:
I believe you met

25:06.833 --> 25:08.866
your husband here last summer,
Lady Babington.

25:08.866 --> 25:10.866
Have you any advice
for one hoping

25:10.866 --> 25:12.666
to find a good match
of her own?

25:12.666 --> 25:15.866
Disdain his every word.

25:15.866 --> 25:19.166
If he persists, marry him.

25:19.166 --> 25:25.766
♪ ♪

25:25.766 --> 25:29.666
(cheering)

25:29.666 --> 25:32.866
And you remain
stubbornly unwed, I see.

25:32.866 --> 25:34.400
Yes, Lady Denham.

25:34.400 --> 25:36.733
Oh, you'd better hurry up,
or you'll miss your chance.

25:36.733 --> 25:39.166
There are some women who choose
not to marry at all.

25:39.166 --> 25:40.866
Oh, don't be absurd!

25:40.866 --> 25:44.033
An unmarried woman is a
worthless pariah

25:44.033 --> 25:47.600
who brings shame and ruin upon
her family.

25:47.600 --> 25:49.433
Regard the unfortunate
Miss Hankins.

25:49.433 --> 25:51.566
No one chooses to be a spinster.

25:51.566 --> 25:54.233
(crowd cheering)
TOM:
Ah, here they come now.

25:54.233 --> 25:56.866
Don't they look magnificent?

25:56.866 --> 26:01.900
♪ ♪

26:01.900 --> 26:08.566
(crowd cheering)

26:08.566 --> 26:10.966
How commanding
the colonel looks!

26:10.966 --> 26:16.333
♪ ♪

26:18.066 --> 26:19.200
What is it?

26:19.700 --> 26:20.833
Edward.

26:22.033 --> 26:25.566
♪ ♪

26:37.033 --> 26:39.566
AUGUSTA:
Leo, come back here!

26:44.666 --> 26:48.566
♪ ♪

26:49.366 --> 26:50.366
(man gasps)

26:50.366 --> 26:51.033
AUGUSTA:
Leo, stop!

26:51.033 --> 26:53.900
(horse whinnying)

26:53.900 --> 26:55.166
(gasping)

26:56.400 --> 26:57.833
(crowd crying out, gasping)

26:57.833 --> 27:00.700
(horse whinnying)

27:02.433 --> 27:03.866
(hooves stomping)

27:05.866 --> 27:09.500
(crowd murmuring, exhaling,
drumming continues)

27:10.466 --> 27:12.100
(gasps)

27:12.100 --> 27:16.300
Are you all right?

27:16.300 --> 27:19.566
(crowd cheering)

27:19.566 --> 27:21.033
(people talking in background)

27:21.033 --> 27:22.766
I do wish you'd marry me,
Arthur.

27:22.766 --> 27:24.300
(chuckles)

27:24.300 --> 27:25.866
Then I would not
have to consider

27:25.866 --> 27:28.000
any more of
these tedious suitors.

27:28.000 --> 27:29.266
Oh, should I be
forced to marry,

27:29.266 --> 27:32.700
you would be top of my list,
but it's not for me.

27:32.700 --> 27:35.600
I am certain Tom will find you
someone worthy yet.

27:35.600 --> 27:37.033
How?

27:37.033 --> 27:39.500
These men do not care who I am.

27:39.500 --> 27:41.066
They care only for my fortune.

27:41.066 --> 27:45.466
Whereas you, Arthur,
treat me with kindness

27:45.466 --> 27:47.500
and respect
and good humor.

27:49.166 --> 27:51.266
But I fear you
are one of a kind.

27:51.266 --> 27:52.933
Oh, I doubt that,
Miss Lambe.

27:52.933 --> 27:54.800
I shall keep an eye out
for a kindred spirit

27:54.800 --> 27:57.700
in search of a wife.
(chuckles)

27:59.633 --> 28:00.900
ARTHUR:
I don't suppose you could

28:00.900 --> 28:04.466
turn a blind eye to
one teeny tiny little bun?

28:04.466 --> 28:06.833
You couldn't live with
yourself, Arthur.

28:10.800 --> 28:12.966
(both chuckle)

28:16.200 --> 28:17.933
LEONORA:
It doesn't hurt.

28:19.633 --> 28:21.733
It's only a scratch.

28:21.733 --> 28:25.100
MARY:
Put him down here.

28:25.100 --> 28:26.900
CHARLOTTE:
There we go.
(grunts)

28:26.900 --> 28:28.966
Alison,
could you fetch some water?
Yes.

28:30.500 --> 28:31.600
What's your name?

28:31.600 --> 28:32.833
Leo.

28:34.233 --> 28:35.400
MARY:
Here.

28:35.400 --> 28:37.233
Thank you.

28:37.233 --> 28:39.666
Your little brother
is very brave.

28:39.666 --> 28:41.200
She is not my brother,
she's my cousin.

28:41.200 --> 28:42.366
She?

28:42.366 --> 28:44.200
Leonora.

28:44.200 --> 28:45.533
And she's not brave,
she's reckless.

28:45.533 --> 28:48.900
Jumping in front of a horse
is an act of rank stupidity.

28:48.900 --> 28:49.933
Well, her leg
needs tending to.

28:49.933 --> 28:51.133
Do you live close by?

28:51.133 --> 28:53.300
You can take the carriage.

28:53.300 --> 28:59.833
♪ ♪

29:02.100 --> 29:03.900
CHARLOTTE:
You've not yet
told me your name.

29:03.900 --> 29:05.366
Miss Augusta Markham.

29:05.366 --> 29:07.800
I'm Charlotte Heywood.

29:07.800 --> 29:09.133
This is quite unnecessary.

29:09.133 --> 29:10.966
We could easily have walked--
it is not such a distance.

29:10.966 --> 29:12.500
I have to ask.

29:12.500 --> 29:14.533
Your cousin is injured,

29:14.533 --> 29:16.566
but you do not seem
the least troubled by it.

29:16.566 --> 29:18.600
Or by the fact
she came within an inch

29:18.600 --> 29:20.633
of being trampled by a horse.

29:20.633 --> 29:22.566
Yet she did not.

29:22.566 --> 29:24.600
So, I see little point
in vexing myself

29:24.600 --> 29:25.833
over something
which didn't happen.

29:25.833 --> 29:27.633
LEONORA:
I wasn't in danger,

29:27.633 --> 29:29.900
and you ruined my mission.

29:29.900 --> 29:31.366
Your mission?

29:31.366 --> 29:35.033
I'm a spy for the
Spanish army and you ruined it.

29:35.033 --> 29:38.133
Well, then, Leo,
I must apologize.

29:38.133 --> 29:39.533
All the same,
I am sure your mother

29:39.533 --> 29:41.000
would rather see you
returned in one piece.

29:41.000 --> 29:42.566
Our mothers are dead.

29:42.566 --> 29:44.400
Both of them?

29:44.400 --> 29:46.000
What of it?

29:46.000 --> 29:50.133
♪ ♪

29:52.866 --> 29:56.400
(birds cawing,
people talking in background)

30:06.166 --> 30:08.100
CHARLES:
Mr. Parker.

30:08.100 --> 30:09.900
Did you enjoy the parade?

30:09.900 --> 30:11.900
ARTHUR:
Mr. Lockhart!

30:11.900 --> 30:13.766
As a matter of fact,
we chose to avoid it.

30:13.766 --> 30:15.666
I fail to see why we should be
so enamored of those

30:15.666 --> 30:17.266
swaggering brutes just
because they polished off

30:17.266 --> 30:18.566
a lot of Frenchmen.

30:18.566 --> 30:19.800
I quite agree.

30:19.800 --> 30:22.233
I happen to be enormously
fond of the French, myself.

30:22.233 --> 30:24.800
Although I know it is
blasphemy to say so.

30:26.066 --> 30:27.166
ARTHUR:
Oh...

30:27.166 --> 30:29.733
May I introduce
my dear friend Miss Lambe.

30:29.733 --> 30:30.700
Miss Lambe.

30:30.700 --> 30:31.733
I must confess
I noticed you

30:31.733 --> 30:32.833
in the Assembly Rooms
yesterday.

30:32.833 --> 30:34.366
How observant.

30:34.366 --> 30:36.566
I wonder what it was
that caught your attention.

30:36.566 --> 30:37.633
It was your expression.

30:37.633 --> 30:39.766
Haughty yet inscrutable.

30:39.766 --> 30:41.100
Interesting.

30:41.100 --> 30:43.266
Because I thought you looked
arrogant and affected.

30:43.266 --> 30:45.100
Oh, I am both of
those things.

30:45.100 --> 30:46.666
I fear I am an open book.

30:48.433 --> 30:49.700
Yet with you,
I find your true character

30:49.700 --> 30:51.100
harder to ascertain.

30:51.100 --> 30:53.433
But perhaps
that's by design.

30:53.433 --> 30:54.966
Perhaps it is simply that

30:54.966 --> 30:57.200
I do not wish
to be known by you.

30:58.700 --> 30:59.733
Come, Arthur.

30:59.733 --> 31:01.500
A pleasure, sir.

31:01.500 --> 31:03.500
À bientôt.

31:03.500 --> 31:05.133
(chuckles)

31:07.033 --> 31:11.566
♪ ♪

31:15.933 --> 31:17.433
CHARLOTTE:
Heyrick Park.

31:17.433 --> 31:19.266
Is that where you live?

31:19.266 --> 31:20.400
I do not live here.

31:20.400 --> 31:22.100
I'm a prisoner.

31:22.100 --> 31:23.433
To date, I have been
held against my will

31:23.433 --> 31:25.033
for 16 months
and 11 days.

31:25.033 --> 31:27.800
LEONORA:
If you hate it so much,
you can leave!

31:27.800 --> 31:30.966
AUGUSTA:
Had I anywhere else to go,
you horrible child,

31:30.966 --> 31:32.333
do you not think I would?

31:32.333 --> 31:34.500
CHARLOTTE:
Oh, stop, please,
there is no need to argue.

31:42.066 --> 31:45.333
♪ ♪

31:51.466 --> 31:52.633
(horse snorting)

32:00.966 --> 32:02.833
(carriage door closes)

32:02.833 --> 32:03.966
(house door opens)

32:07.533 --> 32:10.000
May I help you, Miss...

32:10.000 --> 32:11.800
Miss Heywood.

32:11.800 --> 32:13.400
I just returned Miss Colbourne
and Miss Markham

32:13.400 --> 32:15.900
from the parade, but...

32:16.766 --> 32:18.200
Miss Colbourne's hurt her leg,

32:18.200 --> 32:19.833
and it really does
need seeing to.
Mr. Colbourne told them

32:19.833 --> 32:22.566
expressly not to
go near those soldiers.

32:22.566 --> 32:24.233
He will not be best pleased.

32:24.233 --> 32:26.700
Which is why we're
looking for a governess.

32:26.700 --> 32:28.533
Thank you, Miss Heywood.

32:30.200 --> 32:31.366
(door closes)

32:36.300 --> 32:39.133
Mary tells me
those girls belong to

32:39.133 --> 32:40.933
Alexander Colbourne.

32:40.933 --> 32:42.033
Small wonder they
were so objectionable.

32:42.033 --> 32:43.800
Tom!

32:43.800 --> 32:45.266
Well, you cannot deny
that the man

32:45.266 --> 32:47.366
is a miser and a recluse

32:47.366 --> 32:50.900
and owns not one quality
I could call admirable.

32:50.900 --> 32:52.200
What has this
Mr. Colbourne done

32:52.200 --> 32:53.566
to cause you such offense?

32:53.566 --> 32:54.900
Tried at every turn

32:54.900 --> 32:57.133
to obstruct my improvements,
Charlotte.

32:57.133 --> 32:59.366
If he had his way,
Sanditon would still be

32:59.366 --> 33:00.900
a fishing village.

33:00.900 --> 33:02.466
I've never heard you
mention him before.

33:02.466 --> 33:04.833
That's because I prefer
not to think of him.

33:04.833 --> 33:06.200
And in truth,

33:06.200 --> 33:08.133
he is rarely seen
outside of his estate.

33:08.133 --> 33:10.766
After the death of his wife
some years ago,

33:10.766 --> 33:12.966
Mr. Colbourne
largely withdrew from society.

33:12.966 --> 33:14.466
ARTHUR:
Yeah, they say the precise

33:14.466 --> 33:16.900
circumstances of her death
have never been explained.

33:16.900 --> 33:19.666
MARY:
Oh, Arthur!

33:19.666 --> 33:21.766
Thank you.

33:21.766 --> 33:23.633
I'm sorry to call unannounced--
please.

33:23.633 --> 33:25.000
But I must know.

33:25.000 --> 33:27.600
The child that fell...

33:27.600 --> 33:28.866
CHARLOTTE:
Quite unharmed,
I assure you, sir.

33:28.866 --> 33:31.300
Besides a small cut
to her leg.

33:31.300 --> 33:33.000
I am heartily relieved
to hear it, Miss Heywood.

33:33.000 --> 33:35.833
That she was spared
a far graver outcome

33:35.833 --> 33:38.200
is thanks only to your
quick thinking and courage.

33:38.200 --> 33:39.500
Those are only two of
my sister's

33:39.500 --> 33:41.300
many fine qualities,
Colonel.

33:41.300 --> 33:42.733
Would you join us
for tea, Colonel?

33:42.733 --> 33:44.100
I'd be honored.

33:44.100 --> 33:45.133
MARY:
I'll get another cup.

33:45.133 --> 33:46.466
I'll go.

33:46.466 --> 33:47.700
What a spectacle

33:47.700 --> 33:50.566
your company gave us,
Colonel.

33:50.566 --> 33:54.966
♪ ♪

33:58.200 --> 34:01.100
♪ ♪

34:05.600 --> 34:06.966
I am dying to hear
your first impressions

34:06.966 --> 34:08.100
of Sanditon, Colonel.

34:08.100 --> 34:09.133
I was struck at once

34:09.133 --> 34:11.733
by its natural beauty.

34:11.733 --> 34:14.500
TOM:
It is fair to say that
all who set foot in Sanditon

34:14.500 --> 34:15.933
fall in love on the spot.

34:15.933 --> 34:17.833
Hmm.

34:17.833 --> 34:20.466
Was that your experience,
Miss Heywood?

34:22.233 --> 34:24.466
I am exceedingly fond
of Sanditon.

34:24.466 --> 34:26.233
And the people in it.

34:26.233 --> 34:28.166
TOM:
Yet I shouldn't be surprised
if by summer's end,

34:28.166 --> 34:31.033
you decide to build
a permanent barracks here.

34:31.033 --> 34:32.833
Oh, let's not get ahead

34:32.833 --> 34:34.266
of ourselves, Tom.
(chuckles)

34:34.266 --> 34:35.566
MARY:
The colonel has barely arrived.

34:35.566 --> 34:37.233
LENNOX:
Quite so, Mrs. Parker.

34:37.233 --> 34:39.600
And in truth,
our company doesn't

34:39.600 --> 34:41.400
tend to stay in
any one place for long.

34:41.400 --> 34:42.433
I must say, Colonel,

34:42.433 --> 34:44.533
it does sound a rather
lonely sort of life.

34:44.533 --> 34:47.400
Do you never long to put down
roots of a more permanent sort?

34:47.400 --> 34:50.300
I cannot deny the
thought has crossed my mind.

34:50.300 --> 34:51.800
But to be an
Army officer's wife

34:51.800 --> 34:54.533
requires a particular kind
of forbearance.

34:54.533 --> 34:57.833
Yes, I imagine it would require
quick thinking and courage.

34:57.833 --> 34:59.833
Hmm.

34:59.833 --> 35:01.633
Knowing your husband
might, at any moment,

35:01.633 --> 35:06.033
be shipped across the ocean,
perhaps never to return.

35:06.033 --> 35:07.100
That seems
a price worth paying,

35:07.100 --> 35:08.533
given the life
of an officer's wife

35:08.533 --> 35:10.000
is surely a great deal
more exciting than

35:10.000 --> 35:11.900
that of, say,
a farmer's wife.

35:11.900 --> 35:14.166
Would you not agree,
Charlotte?

35:14.166 --> 35:15.866
That is beside the point,

35:15.866 --> 35:19.533
given I have no intention
of becoming either.

35:19.533 --> 35:22.133
I shall take that
as a sign of sound judgment.

35:22.833 --> 35:25.433
Excuse me a moment.

35:29.066 --> 35:30.400
(door closes)

35:31.433 --> 35:34.200
Believe me, Aunt,
this was not by design.

35:34.200 --> 35:36.166
When I joined the regiment,
I never dreamt the colonel

35:36.166 --> 35:38.200
would bring us here,
of all places.

35:38.200 --> 35:40.666
A remarkable coincidence.

35:40.666 --> 35:42.933
(sighs):
I would never presume to
ask your forgiveness.

35:42.933 --> 35:44.366
I do not deserve it.

35:44.366 --> 35:45.733
But I'm hoping
that I may yet prove

35:45.733 --> 35:47.033
I've seen
the error of my ways.

35:47.033 --> 35:50.066
That I am not the
Edward Denham that I once was.

35:50.066 --> 35:52.366
I find that
extremely difficult to believe.

35:52.366 --> 35:55.133
And while you are here,
you will keep your distance.

35:55.133 --> 35:58.166
Especially from Esther.

35:58.166 --> 36:00.100
She has enough to worry about.

36:01.533 --> 36:03.366
You have my word.

36:13.366 --> 36:16.033
(door closes)

36:16.033 --> 36:18.200
♪ ♪

36:19.733 --> 36:20.700
(sighs)

36:20.700 --> 36:23.300
(people talking in background)

36:23.300 --> 36:25.500
TOM:
And my apologies once again

36:25.500 --> 36:26.966
for Miss Heywood's
abrupt departure.

36:26.966 --> 36:28.466
I hope you will not think
too poorly of her.

36:28.466 --> 36:29.766
On the contrary.

36:29.766 --> 36:32.066
She has only risen
in my estimation.
(horse nickers)

36:33.933 --> 36:35.500
What was the meaning of
Charlotte's behavior,

36:35.500 --> 36:36.566
do you suppose?

36:36.566 --> 36:39.266
I can only guess.

36:39.266 --> 36:45.433
♪ ♪

37:05.033 --> 37:10.933
♪ ♪

37:17.966 --> 37:21.700
SIDNEY (voiceover):
I believe I am my best self,

37:21.700 --> 37:25.033
my truest self,

37:25.033 --> 37:27.366
when I'm with you.

37:33.933 --> 37:36.100
(shutter clatters)

37:38.733 --> 37:40.000
Esther.

37:41.333 --> 37:44.833
I have nothing
to say to you.

37:44.833 --> 37:47.533
My life has been quite empty
without you in it.

37:47.533 --> 37:49.666
I know it's not what you want
to hear, but it's the truth.

37:49.666 --> 37:52.666
All I want to hear is
the door closing behind you.

37:52.666 --> 37:55.566
Is there no part of you
that's felt my absence?

37:55.566 --> 37:57.900
Can you honestly
say that?

37:57.900 --> 38:01.566
Poor, tragic, deluded Edward.

38:01.566 --> 38:03.733
I've not spared you
a second's thought.

38:03.733 --> 38:06.200
Will Lord Babington
be joining you?

38:06.200 --> 38:07.666
He has
business to attend to.

38:07.666 --> 38:09.200
Shame.

38:11.600 --> 38:14.466
I do hope he's
treating you kindly.

38:14.466 --> 38:20.433
He brings me more joy
than you could possibly imagine.

38:27.066 --> 38:28.200
You look well, Esther.

38:28.200 --> 38:31.933
Radiant with health
and happiness.

38:31.933 --> 38:34.233
I have no desire
to cause you further pain

38:34.233 --> 38:36.300
or embarrassment.

38:36.300 --> 38:39.466
From now on,
I'll keep my distance.

38:51.100 --> 38:56.266
♪ ♪

39:09.600 --> 39:13.833
♪ ♪

39:13.833 --> 39:17.000
(object creaks in distance)

39:17.000 --> 39:18.366
(house door closes)

39:27.033 --> 39:29.500
Please do not
be angry with me.

39:29.500 --> 39:31.533
I'm not.

39:31.533 --> 39:32.666
It was badly done,

39:32.666 --> 39:36.400
but I meant no harm by it.

39:36.400 --> 39:38.233
There are things
you do not understand.

39:48.566 --> 39:50.566
I understand perfectly.

39:51.900 --> 39:54.833
You are still
in love with him.

39:54.833 --> 39:56.300
Despite everything.

39:58.433 --> 40:02.966
I am not as naive
as you think.

40:02.966 --> 40:04.200
I hoped, coming back here,

40:04.200 --> 40:06.300
that you could somehow
lay your memories to rest,

40:06.300 --> 40:08.266
but...

40:08.266 --> 40:09.333
Instead,
I fear it has somehow

40:09.333 --> 40:11.033
stirred them up again.
No.

40:12.966 --> 40:16.033
It has given me clarity.

40:19.366 --> 40:22.500
I've realized I can never again
put myself in a man's power.

40:24.666 --> 40:25.766
It's not Ralph.

40:25.766 --> 40:29.633
Or Colonel Lennox.

40:29.633 --> 40:33.533
It is marriage itself.

40:33.533 --> 40:37.866
But how will we live if
we do not marry?

40:37.866 --> 40:42.066
We do not have the freedom of
Georgiana's fortune.

40:42.066 --> 40:45.433
We are poor,
Charlotte.

40:45.433 --> 40:46.933
Wretchedly so.

40:48.333 --> 40:50.700
Three bad harvests
in a row.

40:50.700 --> 40:52.766
Papa cannot afford
to keep us...

40:52.766 --> 40:54.766
Nor would I
expect him to.

40:54.766 --> 40:57.066
I will keep myself.

40:57.066 --> 40:59.166
How?

40:59.166 --> 41:01.766
ALISON:
A governess?

41:01.766 --> 41:03.566
And for Mr. Colbourne,
of all people?

41:03.566 --> 41:04.766
My dear Charlotte...

41:04.766 --> 41:06.966
I appreciate
your concern, Mary.

41:06.966 --> 41:08.166
Think of our poor family.

41:08.166 --> 41:09.600
The shame
you will bring to them.

41:09.600 --> 41:11.533
I see no shame
in earning a living.

41:11.533 --> 41:12.900
MARY:
A governess position

41:12.900 --> 41:14.933
is a last resort
for a young woman.

41:14.933 --> 41:17.166
When circumstances
leave you no alternative.

41:17.166 --> 41:21.166
As I am resolved not to marry,
I will need an income.

41:21.166 --> 41:22.566
As a woman of
three and 20,

41:22.566 --> 41:24.166
what other professions
are available to me?

41:24.166 --> 41:27.133
I cannot have my sister
be a spinster.

41:27.133 --> 41:29.533
This will not do,
Charlotte!

41:31.100 --> 41:34.100
Charlotte.

41:34.100 --> 41:36.766
You are allowed to grieve him.

41:36.766 --> 41:39.833
He has a widow.

41:39.833 --> 41:41.333
It is not my place.

41:42.800 --> 41:43.800
(sighs)

41:43.800 --> 41:48.700
(wildlife chittering)

41:48.700 --> 41:50.233
(door opens)

41:57.566 --> 42:00.700
I think perhaps
I should extend my stay.

42:00.700 --> 42:03.133
If you can bear my company
for a few more weeks.

42:03.133 --> 42:04.833
Oh, I suppose
it serves me right

42:04.833 --> 42:09.600
for being such
an indulgent hostess.

42:09.600 --> 42:11.466
Babington will be away
for a while yet.

42:11.466 --> 42:14.233
I'm not ready to
accept the doctor's opinion.

42:14.233 --> 42:17.066
And in all conscience,
cannot leave you to

42:17.066 --> 42:19.300
the mercy of my stepbrother.
(chuckling)

42:19.300 --> 42:22.766
I hardly need your
protection from Edward.

42:22.766 --> 42:24.766
I have never been
in the least susceptible

42:24.766 --> 42:26.366
to his unctuous charms.

42:26.366 --> 42:29.000
Although it must be said,

42:29.000 --> 42:30.600
the shock of disinheritance

42:30.600 --> 42:34.400
does seem to have provoked some
genuine stirrings of remorse.

42:35.366 --> 42:36.866
Do not be fooled, Aunt.

42:36.866 --> 42:39.400
There's nothing
genuine about it.

42:39.400 --> 42:43.100
(people calling in distance)

42:43.100 --> 42:45.266
Denham.

42:45.266 --> 42:47.033
I must thank you for

42:47.033 --> 42:48.633
recommending Sanditon
as a company outpost.

42:48.633 --> 42:50.300
Oh, honored to
be of service, Colonel.

42:50.300 --> 42:52.866
And your aunt,
was she pleased to see you?

42:52.866 --> 42:54.100
Exceptionally, sir.

42:54.100 --> 42:55.166
And to my great delight,

42:55.166 --> 42:56.866
my stepsister
is currently her guest.

42:56.866 --> 42:59.200
So, it's been
the happiest of reunions.

42:59.200 --> 43:01.633
Captain Fraser tells me
you lost another two guineas

43:01.633 --> 43:03.366
at cards last night.

43:03.366 --> 43:04.433
Was that wise?

43:04.433 --> 43:05.633
Given you have yet
to pay for

43:05.633 --> 43:07.066
your commission?
Oh, rest assured, Colonel.

43:07.066 --> 43:08.966
You'll have your money
within weeks.

43:08.966 --> 43:10.133
I have everything in hand.

43:10.133 --> 43:11.466
Good man.

43:17.166 --> 43:19.400
♪ ♪

43:19.400 --> 43:20.633
ESTHER (voiceover):
There is much excitement

43:20.633 --> 43:24.200
at the arrival of
a company of soldiers,

43:24.200 --> 43:26.600
but I am
altogether indifferent,

43:26.600 --> 43:28.466
since my thoughts are
only of you,

43:28.466 --> 43:30.966
my husband,
and our life to come.

43:30.966 --> 43:35.366
♪ ♪

43:35.366 --> 43:38.866
I do believe the sea air
is doing me the power of good.

43:38.866 --> 43:40.833
The doctor assures me there
is every reason to believe

43:40.833 --> 43:43.066
our prayers
may yet be answered.

43:45.700 --> 43:49.966
♪ ♪

43:49.966 --> 43:53.600
I thought you were coming here
to spend time with me.

43:53.600 --> 43:54.866
To be my friend.

43:54.866 --> 43:57.166
I am your friend,
Georgiana.

43:57.166 --> 43:59.033
I'll forever be your friend.

43:59.033 --> 44:02.033
This does
nothing to change that.

44:02.033 --> 44:04.733
I do not suppose it would help
if I were to pay you?

44:04.733 --> 44:06.733
I could match
whatever he offers.

44:06.733 --> 44:09.233
You know
I could never accept.

44:09.233 --> 44:12.200
I don't want to be
beholden to anyone.

44:12.200 --> 44:15.733
Not even you.

44:15.733 --> 44:18.333
I do understand,
you know?

44:18.333 --> 44:20.266
Sidney and I
were hardly friends,

44:20.266 --> 44:22.500
yet even I feel unmoored.

44:22.500 --> 44:25.766
I can only imagine
how you must feel.

44:27.400 --> 44:30.200
Thank you for
traveling with me, Georgiana.

44:30.200 --> 44:33.433
But from this point on,
I can journey alone.

44:33.433 --> 44:39.833
♪ ♪

44:45.900 --> 44:48.566
(wildlife chittering)

44:51.633 --> 44:56.133
(birds chirping)

45:09.300 --> 45:12.766
(doorbell ringing)

45:12.766 --> 45:15.000
(door opens)

45:18.900 --> 45:23.700
♪ ♪

45:33.500 --> 45:34.700
Mr. Colbourne,

45:34.700 --> 45:38.233
Miss Heywood is here
about the governess position.

45:38.233 --> 45:39.266
She was the young lady

45:39.266 --> 45:41.800
who returned the girls
from the parade.

45:43.266 --> 45:44.666
Thank you.

45:48.000 --> 45:50.200
One moment, Mrs. Wheatley.

45:51.533 --> 45:52.966
Seven 15s?

45:52.966 --> 45:54.333
I beg your pardon?

45:54.333 --> 45:55.533
What are seven 15s?

45:55.533 --> 45:56.766
105.

45:56.766 --> 45:58.033
The capital of
Argentina?

45:58.033 --> 45:59.366
Buenos Aires.

45:59.366 --> 46:01.100
Do you play an
instrument?

46:01.100 --> 46:03.566
The pianoforte,
a little.

46:03.566 --> 46:05.466
Mrs. Wheatley, will you see
this is delivered today, please?

46:05.466 --> 46:07.633
Sir.
Thank you.

46:09.333 --> 46:10.533
(door closes)

46:10.533 --> 46:12.766
Pouvez-vous tenir une
conversation en français?

46:12.766 --> 46:15.033
Oui, monsieur,
je parle bien le français.

46:15.033 --> 46:17.500
Please.

46:21.166 --> 46:23.933
You already met
my daughter and my niece.

46:23.933 --> 46:25.166
Uh, yes, sir.

46:25.166 --> 46:27.433
And that experience
was not sufficient to deter you?

46:27.433 --> 46:29.366
On the contrary.

46:29.366 --> 46:31.266
What did you make of them?

46:31.266 --> 46:34.166
Miss Colbourne
has a keen imagination

46:34.166 --> 46:36.866
and Miss Markham a sharp wit.

46:36.866 --> 46:39.500
By which you mean they are
respectively feral and insolent.

46:39.500 --> 46:42.000
If I had meant that,
sir, I would have said so.

46:42.000 --> 46:43.700
What those children require

46:43.700 --> 46:46.033
is discipline.

46:46.033 --> 46:50.266
Someone who will
take them in hand.

46:50.266 --> 46:51.433
Leonora is nine years old,

46:51.433 --> 46:53.266
and despite what she seems
to think, a girl.

46:53.266 --> 46:55.266
Augusta,
on the other hand, is...

46:56.433 --> 46:58.400
Well, you've met her.

46:58.400 --> 46:59.666
Her attempt
to assert her maturity

46:59.666 --> 47:00.933
only proves the fact
that she is still a child.

47:00.933 --> 47:03.133
I believe
independence of spirit

47:03.133 --> 47:05.366
is something to be encouraged.
Really?

47:05.366 --> 47:08.266
My brother and I
had a governess

47:08.266 --> 47:09.800
who met independence of spirit
with a leather belt.

47:09.800 --> 47:12.033
That's how I
learnt to behave.

47:12.033 --> 47:15.066
Then I feel very sorry
for you and your brother, sir.

47:16.666 --> 47:18.033
I assume you have
a letter of recommendation

47:18.033 --> 47:19.300
from your previous employer?

47:19.300 --> 47:23.000
No, but I've brought
some work to show you.

47:23.000 --> 47:25.133
I have 11 younger brothers
and sisters.

47:25.133 --> 47:26.233
I've been helping our father

47:26.233 --> 47:27.533
with their education
the past year.

47:27.533 --> 47:30.400
Then you are not
a governess at all?

47:30.400 --> 47:31.833
You are here under
false pretenses.

47:33.233 --> 47:36.600
I have some classical learning:
Homer, Heraclitus.

47:36.600 --> 47:38.433
The English poets,
of course.

47:38.433 --> 47:39.400
A deal of Shakespeare.

47:39.400 --> 47:40.800
Mathematics.

47:40.800 --> 47:42.000
What use are poetry

47:42.000 --> 47:44.000
and mathematics
to Augusta?

47:44.000 --> 47:47.000
Society asks that a woman
be accomplished, not learned.

47:47.000 --> 47:48.266
Trust me,
Miss Heywood,

47:48.266 --> 47:49.700
I know what happens

47:49.700 --> 47:52.166
when a woman falls short of
society's expectations.

47:52.166 --> 47:56.133
Then society is wrong,
sir.

47:56.133 --> 47:58.600
Why should your girls
be deprived of an education

47:58.600 --> 48:01.700
on account of their sex?

48:01.700 --> 48:04.900
I would seek to open their minds
to the world around them,

48:04.900 --> 48:07.800
not encourage them
to be meekly submissive.

48:07.800 --> 48:09.766
So, if that is
what you are looking for,

48:09.766 --> 48:13.066
I apologize for
wasting your time.

48:15.633 --> 48:16.766
(door opens)

48:19.666 --> 48:25.500
♪ ♪

48:35.666 --> 48:37.800
(laughs softly)

48:37.800 --> 48:38.833
(barks softly)

48:38.833 --> 48:41.933
(panting)

48:44.633 --> 48:46.200
(barking)

48:50.400 --> 48:54.200
♪ ♪

48:58.866 --> 49:01.433
♪ ♪

49:05.600 --> 49:07.633
(soldiers calling
and laughing)

49:07.633 --> 49:08.900
(chuckles)

49:08.900 --> 49:10.800
ALISON:
What are we to do?

49:10.800 --> 49:12.100
If I'd thought
for even a moment

49:12.100 --> 49:13.866
that returning here
would lead to this...

49:13.866 --> 49:15.100
Be patient with Charlotte.

49:15.100 --> 49:16.200
In time she will reconsider.

49:16.200 --> 49:17.733
Something
will change her mind.

49:17.733 --> 49:18.900
Or someone.

49:18.900 --> 49:20.200
In the meantime,

49:20.200 --> 49:21.500
we must enjoy the summer
while we can.

49:21.500 --> 49:23.300
Is this your carriage?
No.

49:23.300 --> 49:26.900
But I am sure Lord Kingsley
would not mind us borrowing it.

49:26.900 --> 49:30.366
Did you not speak of a desire
to meet a soldier?

49:30.366 --> 49:32.066
(laughing)

49:32.066 --> 49:35.533
ALISON:
You are wicked, Miss Lambe.

49:35.533 --> 49:39.066
♪ ♪

49:41.566 --> 49:43.866
(laughing)

49:49.833 --> 49:52.433
(laughing, squealing)

49:52.433 --> 49:54.800
ALISON:
Look, look!

49:54.800 --> 49:57.100
(men calling)

49:57.100 --> 50:00.733
(laughing)

50:00.733 --> 50:04.533
(laughing)
(men exclaiming)

50:07.366 --> 50:08.966
(men calling indistinctly)

50:10.300 --> 50:12.600
(laughing)

50:14.466 --> 50:16.833
♪ ♪

50:16.833 --> 50:20.566
(laughing)

50:20.566 --> 50:22.700
(men calling indistinctly)

50:24.366 --> 50:26.066
♪ ♪

50:26.066 --> 50:27.766
(wheel squeaking)

50:29.633 --> 50:30.600
(wheel screeching)

50:30.600 --> 50:33.866
(crying out,
carriage crashing)

50:33.866 --> 50:37.666
(men yelling indistinctly)

50:38.633 --> 50:41.000
(horse whinnying)

50:47.733 --> 50:49.033
(sighs)

50:49.033 --> 50:52.700
You're alive,
thank God.

50:59.133 --> 51:00.633
TOM (voiceover):
Mary?

51:00.633 --> 51:03.100
Mary!

51:07.066 --> 51:08.033
What is it, my dear?

51:08.033 --> 51:09.233
ARTHUR:
A letter arrived from

51:09.233 --> 51:10.900
our agent in Antigua.

51:10.900 --> 51:12.200
It seems that
Sidney was not there

51:12.200 --> 51:13.466
to settle his own affairs.

51:17.933 --> 51:21.633
He was there
for Georgiana.

51:21.633 --> 51:27.766
♪ ♪

51:43.000 --> 51:44.233
Miss Heywood.

51:44.233 --> 51:46.866
You did not wait
to hear my decision.

51:46.866 --> 51:48.500
There hardly
seemed much point.
The position is yours.

51:48.500 --> 51:50.433
Assuming you still want it?

51:50.433 --> 51:53.233
You start on Monday.

51:54.666 --> 51:59.466
♪ ♪

52:16.033 --> 52:17.466
♪ ♪

52:17.466 --> 52:20.000
CHARLOTTE:
I am trying to forge a new life,
a new path.

52:20.000 --> 52:22.900
LEONORA:
Miss Heywood said a woman
can be whatever she wants to be.

52:22.900 --> 52:25.900
I thought I engaged you
to make a young lady of Leonora.

52:25.900 --> 52:27.566
CHARLOTTE:
They seem almost strangers
to each other.

52:27.566 --> 52:30.033
But I'm not about to give up
on something I've barely begun.

52:30.033 --> 52:32.333
GEORGIANA:
I've had my fill of suitors.

52:32.333 --> 52:35.466
If I marry,
it will be on my terms.

52:35.466 --> 52:38.100
LENNOX:
You're quite unlike any woman
I've ever met,

52:38.100 --> 52:40.233
Miss Heywood.

52:40.233 --> 52:42.466
CHARLOTTE:
Sometimes it's hard
to gain a sense

52:42.466 --> 52:43.500
of a man's true character.

52:43.500 --> 52:46.033
I believe you have a rival.

52:46.033 --> 52:48.266
ALISON:
He is approaching the house
in his uniform!

52:48.266 --> 52:50.766
CARTER:
I am a tongue-tied buffoon
in her presence.

52:50.766 --> 52:52.766
FRASER:
He is unforgivably

52:52.766 --> 52:53.933
handsome, after all.

52:53.933 --> 52:55.633
Are you mocking me?

52:55.633 --> 52:57.700
GEORGIANA:
Do not betray your feelings
too readily.

52:57.700 --> 52:58.900
(yelps)

52:58.900 --> 53:00.200
CAPTAIN: Fire!
(guns fire)

53:00.200 --> 53:01.266
♪ ♪

53:01.266 --> 53:03.566
I am looking for passion!

53:03.566 --> 53:04.933
Emotion!

53:04.933 --> 53:06.633
Honesty!

53:06.633 --> 53:09.200
CHARLOTTE:
Love is not as simple
as you seem to think.

